title: marine_day
body:
From "Wikipedia":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marine_Day:

"Marine Day (海の日, Umi no Hi), also known as 'Ocean Day' or 'Sea Day', is a public holiday in Japan usually celebrated on the third Monday in July. The purpose of the holiday is to give thanks for the ocean's bounty and to consider the importance of the ocean to Japan as a maritime nation. Many people take advantage of the holiday and summer weather to take a beach trip. Other ocean-related festivities are observed as well."

On this day, various Japanese artists will post an image of characters in their [[swimsuit]]s to celebrate the holiday. Apply this tag when Marine Day is mentioned by the artist, either within the image or in the commentary.

body:
A [b]plasma globe[/b] or [b]plasma lamp[/b] (also called [[plasma]] ball, dome, sphere, tube or orb, depending on shape) is (usually) a clear glass sphere filled with a mixture of various noble gases with a high-voltage electrode in the center of the sphere. title: excel_saga
body:
A comedy manga series by [[Rikudou Koushi]], serialized in Young King Ours from 1996 until 2011. An anime version was made in 1999-2000, with 25 of the 26 episodes broadcast in Japan due to the last episode being intentionally too violent and obscene, so it was released only on DVD. The manga's jokes focus on Japanese society, while the anime's are homages to various series and genres. Excel Saga would later spawn the two-episde OVA [[Puni Puni Poemi]].

It follows the plights of the evil organization ACROSS in its attempts to take over Fukuoka City, and eventually the world. However they fail repeatedly due to the first officer [[Excel]]'s insane hyperactivity, inept decision making, and her fanatical one-sided love for ACROSS' leader [[Ilpalazzo]].

title: t'au
body:
A faction from [[warhammer 40k|Warhammer 40,000]], characterized by their blue-skinned, humanoid forms and extensive use of [[mecha]]. The T'au would go from a primitive species to a spacefaring civilization capable of standing against the might of the [[imperium of man|Imperium]] in only a few millenia, driven by a philosophy they call the "Greater Good". Nominally a lighter faction within the grim darkness of the far future, the T'au have forged alliances with a number of other species, such as the reptillian Kroot and the insectoid Vespids, and have even recruited a number of human defectors from the Imperium. Beneath that, however, their ruling caste, the Ethereals, have kept their people ignorant of the dangers of the wider galaxy and may have sinister intentions for their civilization.

Nicknamed the "Weaboo Space Communists" by Imperial players as their designs appear to be heavily based on Japanese science fiction media and their ideology of the "Greater Good" is seen as collectivist enough to be compared/equated to communism, tongue-in-cheek or not.

title: intellivision
body:
The [b]Intellivision[/b] is an American home [[game console]] released by "Mattel":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mattel Electronics in 1979. 

The name Intellivision is a portmanteau of "Intelligent [[Television]]". Development of the console began in 1977, the same year as the introduction of its main competitor, the Atari 2600.
 
From 1980 to 1983 over 3 million Intellivision units were sold. In 1984 Mattel sold the Intellivision business to a former Mattel Electronics executive and investors that would become INTV Corporation. ROM [[game cartridge]]s development started in 1978 and continued until 1990 when the Intellivision was discontinued. 

In 2009, video game website IGN named the Intellivision the No. 14 greatest video game console of all time. It remained Mattel's only video game console until the release of the [[HyperScan]] in 2006.

h4. Rival consoles from its era

title: sword_art_online_alternative:_gun_gale_online
body:
[b]Sword Art Online Alternative: Gun Gale Online[/b] is a light novel spin-off series of [[Sword Art Online]] written by Shigusawa Keiichi, with supervision by Kawahara Reki, and illustrated by [[Kuroboshi Kouhaku]].  An anime adaptation aired Spring 2018 and a second season was announced in July of 2023.

The series is about Kohiruimaki Karen, a young college student who has a complex about her height of 183 cm (~72 in).  Enticed by the idea of being able to be someone else through a game avatar, Karen gets into Virtual Reality Massively Multiplayer Online Role Play Games (VRMMORPGs) wanting to be someone with a shorter stature.  She starts with ALfheim Online (ALO) using the name LLENN, but finds that the randomly assigned game avatar is too tall.  Advised by one of her friends, Karen transfers her account to various other games in the hopes of receiving a random avatar to her liking. She eventually settles on Gun Gale Online (GGO), as her randomly assigned avatar is a "chibi" with a height of 150 cm (~59 in).  The story starts after Karen becomes friends with an online player named Pitohui, who gets Karen to participate in a team-based tournament called Squad Jam.

title: game_boy_(original)
body:
The original Nintendo [[Game Boy]], released in 1989 as a followup to the [[Game & Watch]] handhelds. This model is recognizable for its dot-matrix screen, light gray color, and size. While less powerful than its competitors, the [[Sega Game Gear]] and [[Atari Lynx]], its much longer battery life and popular games such as [[Tetris]] led the Game Boy to become one of the best selling video game consoles of all time, only being discontinued in 2003. 

The model had two revisions: the [[Game Boy Pocket]] and the [[Game Boy Light]], and one hardware upgrade: the [[Game Boy Color]]. Succeeded by the [[Game Boy Advance]] line.

title: sardaukar
body:
A fictional organization of elite [[warrior]]s from the [[dune_(series)|DUNE]] series.

They are completely loyal to [[Emperor Shaddam IV]], ruler of the known universe.

The [b]Sardaukar[/b] are a penal [[army]] secretly trained on the inhospitable Imperial prison planet [[Salusa Secundus]], and the harsh conditions there ensure that only the strongest and most "ferocious" men survive. The weaker ones are sacrified during training and their blood used in bloody rituals to ensure their loyalty to the Emperor. 

Sardaukar training emphasizes ruthlessness, near-suicidal disregard for personal safety, and the use of cruelty as a standard psy-ops weapon in order to weaken opponents with terror. Their uniforms are described as gray with silver and gold trim.

title: joseph_stalin
body:
[b]Joseph Vissarionovich Stalin[/b] (born Ioseb Besarionis dzе Jugashvili)
(December 18, 1878 - March 5, 1953)

Second Leader of the [[Soviet|Soviet Union]] and Leader of Soviet Union in [[World War II]]. Infamous for the "Great Purge" politics that wiped out a significant portion of the [[soviet_army|Red Army]]'s officers, as well as a large number of civilians just prior to Nazi Germany's invasion. He would ultimately defeat Germany at an extremely high cost in casualties and eventually died under suspicious circumstances. A few years after his death, he was denounced by his successor [[Nikita Khrushchev]].

title: shoukaku_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
A [[World War II]] [[aircraft carrier]] operated by the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]].

"Soaring Crane"

Lead ship of her class, approved in the 1937 3rd Supplementary Program. Designed as improved version of the [[hiryuu_(aircraft_carrier)|Hiryu]] with heavier armor, often considered to be the most successful IJN carrier design. 

After the [[Battle of Midway]] the air spaces around the aviation fuel tanks were filled with concrete. She was one of the six carriers involved in the [[Pearl Harbor]] attack and was later sunk in the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] from 3 torpedoes by the US submarine [i]Cavalla[/i].

title: reichsadler
body:
The [b][i]Reichsadler[/i][/b] ("Imperial Eagle") is a German [[heraldry|heraldic]] emblem used since the Holy Roman Empire as a symbol of the [[germany|German]] State, adopted by the German Empire as the national emblem. Its use as the National Emblem continued under the Weimar Republic. The Weimar version was re-adopted by the West Germany and modern-day Federal German Republic as the [i]Bundesadler[/i]. 

Despite its medieval origin, the term [i]Reichsadler[/i] in common English understanding and here refers to the [b][[Nazi]]-era[/b] version that consists of a monochrome [[eagle]] facing to its side, with straight outstretched wings, and both talons clutching a circular wreath containing a [[swastika]]. This also includes the variants, such as the [i]Parteiadler[/i] (NSDAP party emblem, left-facing) and the [[Luftwaffe]] one (curved wings with single talon clutching). 

h4. See also

title: souryuu_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
A [[World War II]] Japanese [[aircraft carrier]] that took part in the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]].

Quoting from Conway (who spelled her as Soryu):

"[b]Soryu[/b], built under the 1931-32 Supplementary Programme, was the model for nearly all the later [[Japan]]ese carriers: fast, lightly built, and intended to deliver blows but not receive them. The flight deck was 711ft 6in x 85ft 4in, and the two hangers were served by three lifts. The small island was to starboard, and just abaft two funnels discharged almost horizontally just below flight deck level. Soryu was hit by 3 bombs from US dive-bombers in the [[Battle of Midway]], burst into flames, and blew up when the fires reached the aviation fuel tanks."

h4.External links

* "Wikipedia article":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_aircraft_carrier_S%C5%8Dry%C5%AB]

title: akagi_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
[[Aircraft carrier]] of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) converted from an unfinished Amagi-class battlecruiser of same name, saw service in [[World War II]] and 2nd Sino-Japanese War. 

Served as the flagship of the First Air Fleet and led the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941. Was sunk during the [[Battle of Midway]] with the loss of 267 men months later. 

Akagi's noticeable features were her triple flight deck set-up (feature she shared with converted Tosa-class battleship [[kaga_(aircraft_carrier)|Kaga]]) during late 20s and early 30s, and her port side island (shared with purpose built aircraft carrier Hiryu) after her modernization during mid-30s.

title: hiryuu_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
A [[World War II]] Japanese [[aircraft carrier]] that took part in the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]].

Quoting from Conway (who spelled her as Hiryu):

"[b]Hiryu[/b] (1931-32 Supplementary Programme) was a slightly enlarged and modified [[souryuu_(aircraft_carrier)|Soryu]]; the beam was increased by 1m for a 20 per cent increase in oil capacity, the protection was strengthened and the forecastle raised by a deck. The flight deck was 711ft 6in x 88ft 6in, and as in Soryu the two hangers were served by three lifts. The island was almost amidships and to port (the second and last Japanese carrier with this arrangement) where it partly balanced the two horizontally-discharging funnels to starboard. Hiryu was hit by 4 bombs from US dive-bombers in the [[Battle of Midway]], wrecking flight deck and hangers; she had to be abandoned and scuttled, the last of the 4 Japanese carriers sunk in the Battle."

title: vsq
body:
The [b]Voice Sequence[/b] (.VSQ) file format was the file format used to store musical note and vocal data for the VOCALOID2 software. This format eventually was replaced by VOCALOID3's VSQX file format, which can save more data and VOCALOID3-engine-specific details.

Use this tag for any image that shows the interface of the software (Piano Roll, Music Notes, Syllables and Phonemes) or a representation of said file.

body:

title: rifle_grenade
body:
A specialized type of [[explosive|grenade]] that uses a [[rifle]]-based launcher rather than being thrown by hand. Some of them look similar to [[mortar shell]]s. Rifle grenades are attached onto the muzzle, and propelled by a blank [[ammunition|cartridge]] inserted into the chamber of the [[gun]].

Modern use of rifle grenades has been widely phased out in favour of [[underbarrel grenade launcher]]s.

title: barrett_mrad
body:
The [b]Barrett MRAD[/b] (Multi-role Adaptive Design) is a [[bolt action]] [b][[sniper rifle]][/b] designed by [[Barrett]] to meet the requirements of the SOCOM PSR. Available in multiple chamberings such as the .338 Lapua Magnum, it is based on the [[Barrett M98B]] with modifications and improvements.
Visually recognizable by its magazine well with curved lips and rectangular indentations, skeletonized [[folding stock]] with cheek pad, and AR-15-like lower receiver shape. 

h1. See also

title: gammon_bomb
body:
The [b]Gammon bomb[/b], officially known as the [b]No. 82 grenade[/b] was a [[united_kingdom|British]] hand [[grenade]] used during [[World War II]].

It was an improvised hand-thrown bomb used by the Home Guard, the [[Special Air Service]] and the Resistance, especially suitable for the destruction of parked [[aircraft]] or vehicles. An explosive charge was wrapped in fabric and sewn to an impact fuse that detonated on sharp contact.

title: 2_fuel_4_ammo_11_steel
body:
A nickname for [[Kantai Collection]]'s [[naka (kancolle)|Naka]]. It comes from the resources you get from dismantling her: 2 fuel, 4 ammo, and 11 steel.  Since Naka is such a common drop in battle, or the typical result of a failed attempt to create a much more impressive ship, many players will reflexively scrap her every time they get her, leading to the nickname. Although to be exact, you actually get 2-2-10 from scrapping Naka alone, if one also scraps the gun a freshly dropped or constructed Naka comes with, you get 2 ammo and 1 steel to make the 2-4-11.

It also among the first [[meme|memes]] that came about from the Kantai Collection fanbase. 

Use this tag when the specified number of objects appear in the image, or some reference to the number 2-4-11 is made. Can also be used as a generic reference to dismantling Naka, but it [i]must[/i] be Naka who is the victim; no other shipgirl qualifies for this tag.

title: iwi_x95
body:
The [B]IWI X95[/B] (formerly Micro-Tavor, MTAR or MTAR-21) is a compact [[bullpup]] [[assault rifle]] designed and produced by Israel Weapon Industries, predominantly available in 5.56×45mm NATO.
It can be distinguished from the [[iwi tavor|TAR-21]] series by the location of its charging handle which is closer to the pistol grip, straight lower buttstock shape (less jaggy outline) and a magazine release near the pistol grip. May have standard trigger guard or one that completely encloses the pistol grip. See post #3059189.

This includes one of its major variants, the 9×19mm IWI X95 [[submachine gun|SMG]] (post #6105143). Tag accordingly.

title: gewehr_88
body:
The [b]Gewehr 88[/b] was a late 19th-century German [[bolt action]] [b][[rifle]][/b], adopted in 1888. Chambered in propietary M/88 or 7.92×57mm Mauser round, the [[gun]] features a straight bolt handle, ladder-type [[flip-up sight|flip-up rear sight]], 5-round fixed magazine with trigger guard integrated onto it.
This also applies to the Hanyang Type 88, an unlicensed Chinese copy with lack of barrel shroud and Mauser-style tangent rear sight.

body:
The [b]HS2000[/b] ([i]Hrvatski Samokres[/i]) is a series of hammerless, striker-fired, polymer-framed [b][[handgun]][/b], available in various calibers. Designed by Marko Vuković and manufactured since 1999 by HS Produkt in Karlovac, Croatia. It is marketed as the Springfield Armory XD and XD-M series in the US. title: namazuo_toushirou
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character.

A [[wakizashi]], converted from a [[naginata]]. One of the many Toushirou brothers, and is especially close to [[Honebami Toushirou]], whose quieter personality contrasts his. 

He has an outgoing, cheerful and somewhat spacey personality. His occasionally odd behavior is most notable in his Internal affairs quote "馬糞は嫌いなやつになげるー" ("I'll throw horse poop at those I hate~"), which naturally results in fanworks giving him a strange fixation on horse poop. He lost some memories due to being burned in a fire during the siege on Osaka Castle, but he claims he doesn't let his memory loss overwhelm him. However, there are indications that it bothers him more than he lets on.  

He has [[long hair|long]] [[black hair]] tied in a [[ponytail]], along with a prominent [[ahoge]], and [[purple eyes]]. His usual outfit is the [[military uniform]] worn by most of the other Awataguchi swords, along with a black [[necktie]] and black [[sode]] on one shoulder. His [[Namazuo Toushirou (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form gives him [[high heels]] and more elaborate armor, and his hairstyle has changed to a [[high ponytail]].

Often compared to [[Shigure (kancolle)|]], with his [[black hair]] and his prominent [[ahoge]] making him look rather like a male version of her.

[i]Namazuo[/i] (鯰尾) means "[[catfish]] tail", which is reflected in his Kiwame form with the sode on his right arm resembling a catfish.

title: honebami_toushirou
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character.

A [[wakizashi]] converted from a [[naginata]], and one of the many Toushirou brothers. Like [[Namazuo Toushirou]], he suffers from memory loss due to a fire (in Honebami's case, he was burned in the Great Fire of Meireki in 1657), but he has lost far more of his memories and is much more quiet and withdrawn than Namazuo is. He dislikes being touched and is not fond of interacting with any of the swords other than Namazuo, though he is fond of horses.

He has [[white hair]] (with the usual superposition with grey and silver) and he has [[purple eyes]] like Namazuo. He wears the same [[military uniform]] as most of the other Awataguchi swords, along with a black [[necktie]], [[sode]], and [[white gloves]]. His [[Honebami Toushirou (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form gives him [[high heels]] and more elaborate armor, and his hair has grown slightly longer in the front.

[i]Honebami[/i] (骨喰) means "bone-eater", and he is sometimes depicted with [[bone|bones]] or a [[skeleton]] as his [[object namesake]]. His armor in his Kiwame form becomes somewhat skeletal in appearance to reflect this.

After his Kiwame remodel, [spoiler]he finally regains his memories. Honebami learns that he was not burned like Ichigo and Namazuo at Osaka, and it was the pain of being left behind (which ultimately saved him) when many of his brothers were burned, coupled with the fires of Meireiki burning him that caused his amnesia. After returning, he's still troubled about his memories, but he's more friendlier with the Saniwa (also revealing he doesn't dislike being touched).[/spoiler]

Voiced by Suzuki Yuuto. Artist is [[tndkworks]].

title: touken_ranbu
body:
[b]Touken Ranbu[/b] (刀剣乱舞, lit. "Boisterous Sword Dance", often abbreviated [i]Tourabu[/i]) is a Japanese free-to-play browser game developed by Kadokawa Games and [[Nitroplus]] released in January 2015. A mobile version of the game called [i]Touken Ranbu Pocket[/i] was released in March 2016.

The gameplay typically centers around controlling and managing [i]touken danshi[/i] (刀剣男士, lit. "sword warriors"), male personifications of historical Japanese [[sword]]s. Players assume the role of a [[saniwa_(touken_ranbu)|]] (審神者) that creates these characters in order to fight against [[jikan sokougun|monstrous]] [[kebiishi_(touken_ranbu)|enemies]] within different eras. Like in [[Kantai Collection]], battling is automated, but players can manually forge, repair, and team up their characters.

The game has two anime adaptations: one called [[Touken Ranbu: Hanamaru]] which is animated by Dogakobo and began airing in October 2016, and another, [[Katsugeki/Touken Ranbu]], animated by Ufotable which begain airing in July 2017. The game also has a series of musicals ([[Musical Touken Ranbu]]) and stage plays based on it.

title: jabulani
body:
The [[Adidas]] Jabulani is the official [[soccer_ball|match ball]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. Jabulani means "rejoice"/"bring joy and happiness"/"to celebrate" in Zulu.

The 11 colors pay tribute to both [[soccer|soccer/football]] and the country in which Africa’s first-ever [[World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] was held, with yellow, red, and black being the stand out colors. The grip’n’groove texture were supposed to allows for maximum control, stable flight, and perfect grip under all conditions.

However, the Jabulani gained negative reception from many footballers. As the ball is designed to be "the roundest football ever made," it is too slippery to be held by goalkeepers, as well as too hard to control by players.

title: pepsi_japan_cola_challenge_(meme)
body:
A series of promos run by [[Pepsi]] in Japan for its Japan Cola, starring soccer player "Honda Keisuke":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keisuke_Honda]. In the original promo, running from April 9th to April 19th, 2019, Twitter users who followed Pepsi Japan's Twitter account would reply to "this post":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1115434153913143296] (or "its":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1117970868011880448] "reposts":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1118695643038527488] as the end date approached) by "playing" a virtual version of [[rock paper scissors|rock, paper, scissors]] against Keisuke. After a period of time, an automated response of Honda’s move was given ("example":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1118695772315430912]). This format would be similarly used for the second and third runs of this promo, with the "second":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1148049061674704896] involving a "card battle":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1151310550720307200] (example of response "given":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1151431492028882945]), running from July 8th to July 22nd, 2019, and the "third":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1183925460461182977] involving a coin toss, one side having a K and the other H (example of response "given":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1183940981013528576]), running from October 15th to October 28th, 2019. A "fourth":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1260026910643572736] campaign ran from May 12th to May 22nd, 2020, once more having users play a game of rock, paper, scissors against Keisuke. A "fifth":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1285031673617408004] campaign ran from July 21st to July 27th, where, "based":[https://twitter.com/pepsi_jpn/status/1285046774122651649] on the day, folks challenged Keisuke in one of the three previous games.

Consecutive challenges, such as from June 22 to July 5th, 2021, would not feature Keisuke.

The original promo was a campaign allowing people to win coupons to be exchanged for 600-mL bottles of Japan Cola at [[FamilyMart]] or [[Lawson]], with players attempting to win coupons by replying to the aforementioned post. It was infamous for being extremely difficult and nearly impossible to win in "with a rate of 0.41% as calculated by one user":[https://twitter.com/OK_im_fine_now/status/1117822329579376640], with subsequent promos keeping up the infamy.

h4. External links

* "Challenge Keisuke Honda in Rock-Paper-Scissors and win Pepsi!":[https://wowjapan.asia/2019/04/challenge-keisuke-honda-in-rock-paper-scissors-and-win-pepsi/]
* "Japanese netizens dismayed at abysmal win rate of Pepsi Japan’s rock-paper-scissors promotion":[https://soranews24.com/2019/04/22/japanese-netizens-dismayed-at-abysmal-win-rate-of-pepsi-japans-rock-paper-scissors-promotion/]

title: guadalcanal_(island)
body:
A large [[island]] in the South Pacific seas.

[b]Guadalcanal[/b] (/ˌɡwɑːdəlkəˈnæl/; indigenous name: [i]Isatabu[/i]) is the principal island in Guadalcanal Province of Solomon Islands, located in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, northeast of [[Australia]]. 

It is the largest island in Solomon Islands by area and the second-largest by population (after Malaita). The island is mainly covered in dense tropical rainforest and has a mountainous hinterland. Guadalcanal was first charted by westerners during the Spanish expedition of Álvaro de Mendaña in 1568. The name comes from the village of Guadalcanal, in the province of Seville, in Andalusia, [[Spain]], birthplace of Pedro de Ortega Valencia, a member of Mendaña's expedition.

title: battle_of_arnhem
body:
[b]The Battle of Arnhem[/b] was a battle of [[World War II]] at the vanguard of the Allied [[Operation Market Garden]]. 

It was fought in and around the Dutch city of [[Arnhem]], the town of Oosterbeek, the villages Wolfheze and Driel and the vicinity from 17 to 26 September 1944 and ended in [[germany|German]] victory. The Allies were poised to enter the Netherlands after sweeping through France and Belgium in the summer of 1944, after the [[Invasion of Normandy]]. 

The 1st Airborne Division landed some distance from its objectives and was hampered by unexpected resistance, especially from elements of the 9th and 10th SS Panzer Divisions. Only a small force was able to reach the [[john_frost_bridge|Arnhem road bridge]] while the advance of the main body of the division was stopped on the outskirts of the town. XXX Corps was unable to advance north from Nijmegen in the [[Battle of Nijmegen]] as quickly as planned and the British airborne troops were not relieved according to schedule. After four days, the small British force at the bridge was overwhelmed and the rest of the division trapped in a small pocket north of the river. The paratroops could not be sufficiently reinforced by the Poles or XXX Corps when they arrived on the southern bank, nor by Royal Air Force supply flights. After nine days of fighting, the remnants of the division were withdrawn in Operation Berlin. The Allies were unable to advance further with no secure bridges over the Nederrijn and the front line stabilised south of Arnhem. The 1st Airborne Division lost nearly three quarters of its strength and did not see combat again.

title: battle_of_the_bulge
body:
[b]The Battle of the Bulge[/b], also known as [b]the Ardennes Offensive[/b], was the last major German offensive campaign on the Western Front during [[World War II]]. 

The battle lasted for five weeks from 16 December 1944 to 28 January 1945, towards the end of the war in Europe. It was launched through the densely forested Ardennes region between Belgium and [[Luxembourg]]. The goal of the German offensive was to seize the harbor at Antwerp, an important Ally source of supplies, equipment and military support, so they could stop the eventual Allied advance into [[Germany]]. In order to reach it before the Allies could regroup and bring their superior air power to bear, German mechanized forces had to seize the roadways through eastern [[Belgium]] as soon as possible.

The Germans achieved a total surprise attack on the morning of 16 December, due to a combination of Allied overconfidence, preoccupation with Allied offensive plans, and poor aerial reconnaissance due to bad weather. American forces bore the brunt of the attack and their fierce resistance on the northern shoulder of the offensive, around Elsenborn Ridge, and in the south, around Bastogne, blocked German access to key roads to the northwest and west that they counted on for success. 

The battle ended with an Allied [[victory]] and a significant [[defeat]] and depletion of the already exhausted German forces in fuel, armor and soldiers. From among the Americans' peak strength of 610,000 troops there were 81,000 battle casualties, including at least 8,400 killed. The "Bulge" was the largest and bloodiest single battle fought by the [[United States]] in World War II and the third-deadliest campaign in American military history.

h4. See also

* [[Siege of Bastogne]]

title: battle_of_remagen
body:
[b]The Battle of Remagen[/b] was an 18-day battle during the Allied invasion of [[Germany]] in the last part of [[World War II]], from 7 to 25 March 1945, when [[united_states|American]] forces unexpectedly captured the Ludendorff Bridge over the Rhine intact. 

The U.S. soldiers were able to succesfully hold it against hard German opposition and build additional temporary crossings. The presence of a bridgehead across the Rhine advanced by three weeks the Western Allies' planned crossing of the Rhine into the German interior and greatly accelerated the fall of The Third Reich and the [[victory]] of Allied forces in Europe.

title: winter_offensive
body:
[b]The winter campaign of 1941–1942[/b], also known as [b]The Winter Offensive[/b], was the name given by [[Soviet]] [[military]] command to the period  from 5 December 1941 to 7 May 1942 that marked the commencement of the [b]Moscow Strategic Offensive Operation[/b] (better known as [b]the Battle of Moscow[/b]) against [[Nazi]] [[Germany]] in [[World War II]]. 

The Soviet defensive effort frustrated [[Adolf Hitler]]'s attack on [[Moscow]], the capital and largest city of the [[Soviet Union]]. Moscow was one of the primary military and political objectives for the Axis forces in their invasion of the Soviet Union.

The opening phase of the [[soviet_army|Red Army]] strategic counter-offensive operations in the Soviet Union was a major albeit costly Soviet [[victory]].

title: prague_offensive
body:
[b]The Prague offensive[/b] (Russian: Пражская стратегическая наступательная операция, romanized: [i]Prazhskaya strategicheskaya nastupatel'naya operatsiya[/i], lit. 'Prague strategic offensive') was the last major [[military]] operation of [[World War II]] in Europe. 

The offensive was fought on the Eastern Front from 6 May to 11 May 1945. Fought concurrently with the Prague uprising, the offensive significantly helped the liberation of [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1945. The offensive was one of the last engagements of World War II in Europe and continued after [[Nazi]] [[Germany]]'s unconditional capitulation on 8/9 May.

The city of Prague was ultimately liberated by the [[Soviet Union]] during the Prague offensive. All of the German troops of Army Group Centre (Heeresgruppe Mitte) and many of Army Group Ostmark (formerly known as Army Group South) were killed or captured, or fell into the hands of the Allies after the capitulation.

title: battle_of_the_dnieper
body:
[b]The Battle of the Dnieper[/b] was a military campaign that took place in 1943 on the Eastern Front of [[World War II]]. 

Being one of the largest operations of the war, it involved almost four million troops at one point and stretched over a 1,400 kilometres (870 mi) front. Over four months, the eastern bank of the Dnieper was recovered from [[Nazi]] [[germany|German]] forces by five of the [[soviet army|Red Army]]'s fronts, which conducted several assault river crossings to establish several lodgements on the western bank. 

2,438 Red Army soldiers were awarded the title Hero of the Soviet Union for their involvement.

title: arc_de_triomphe
body: A massive "triumphal arch":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triumphal_Arch in [[Paris]], one of its most famous monuments. It was conceived by [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] to celebrate France's victory against combined Austrian and Russian forces at Austerlitz in 1805. Its full name is the Arc de Triomphe de l'Étoile, and it those who fought and died for France in the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, with the names of all French victories and generals inscribed on its inner and outer surfaces. Beneath its vault lies France's Tomb of the Unknown Soldier from World War I, which together with the United Kingdom's at Westminster Abbey in London were the first of their kind. The arch stands at the western end of the Champs-Élysées at the centre of Place Charles de Gaulle, formerly named Place de l'Étoile, the étoile or "star" being so named because it sits in the middle of a juncture formed by the Champs-Élysées and eleven other radiating streets. h4.See also * "Official site (Centre des Monuments Nationaux – French/English/Spanish)":[https://www.paris-arc-de-triomphe.fr/] * "Wikipedia":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_de_triomphe * Pixiv tag search: エトワール凱旋門 (Arc de Triomphe) or simply 凱旋門 (Triumphal arch)

title: kikou_senki_dragonar
body:
[b]Kikou Senki Dragonar[/b], also known as [b]Metal Armor Dragonar[/b], is a 48 episode [[mecha]] anime [[science fiction]] TV series, created by Nippon Sunrise (later renamed [[sunrise_(company)|Sunrise]] during production) that aired from 1987 to 1988. 

Devised shortly after the release of Mobile Suit [[Gundam ZZ]], Dragonar was intended to be both a "starter" series to get new fans into mecha anime, and a potential successor to the Gundam franchise. In fact, its concept and plot are said to be a renewal of [[mobile_suit_gundam|the first Gundam]]; and its mecha were designed by [[Ookawara Kunio]], the mechanical designer for most of the [[Gundam]] series.

Though the series enjoyed good ratings and earned a loyal fan following, it failed to surpass Gundam and ended up as a single series, probably due to its light, ZZ Gundam–like take on the real robot mecha genre. [[Video game]] developer "Banpresto":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banpresto had Dragonar appear in two of its popular franchises, [[Super Robot Wars]] and [[Another Century's Episode]]; fans responded positively, and Sunrise acknowledged them in 2005 by releasing a memorial DVD collection of the series, a remastered version of the previous two-part laserdisc box set released years before.

title: gran_class
body:
The nicest available accommodation on [[Shinkansen]] trains. Gran class seating is found on [[e5 hayabusa|E5]]/[[h5 hayabusa|H5]] trains used on Hayabusa, Hayate, Yamabiko, and Nasuno services on the Tohoku and Hokkaido Shinkansen, and E7/W7 trains used on Kagayaki, Hakutaka, Tsurugi, Asama, Toki, and Tanigawa services on the Joetsu and Hokuriku Shinkansen. Seating is in a 2+1 configuration, with the legroom, seat width, and recline being greater than that of the green car seen on all other [[Shinkansen]] routes. The seats are cream leather with a white headrest, and feature power adjustability, a fold-up leg rest, and a reading light. The gran class cabin has only 18 seats and is located in either the first or last car of the train, that being car 10 of [[e5 hayabusa|E5]]/[[h5 hayabusa|H5]], and car 12 of E7/W7 trains. In addition to luxurious seating, complimentary food and drinks, and hostess services are also included.

h4. External links
* "East Japan Railway Company":[https://www.jreast.co.jp/granclass/en/]

title: center_axis_relock_stance
body:
A gun-wielding stance invented before 2011, later popularized by the [[John Wick]] film series. The stance was designed as an effective shooting system for close-quarters self-defense, while minimizing recoil and the user's target profile. The stance has the gun hold close to the body, the body bladed towards the target, with the shoulders placed almost perpendicular to the target (or parallel to the gun, if that makes more sense), supporting shoulder pointed more forward.

[[John Wick (character)|]], and [[Nishikigi Chisato]] of [i][[Lycoris Recoil]][/i] use it.

title: nemesis_prime
body:
Nemesis Prime is an antagonist character from the [[Transformers]] series and essentially a dark counterpart to [[Optimus Prime]]. While he is usually a [[Decepticon]], there are takes on the character with different origins, such as in [[transformers armada|Armada]] where he is a being related to [[Unicron]] and in [[Transformers: The Last Knight|The Last Knight]] where the name is used for Optimus Prime's Quintessa-induced [[dark persona]].

His Japanese name is [b]Black Convoy[/b]. [[Transformers Car Robots|Car Robots]] presents an unusual case of the character, where his name is Black Convoy in the original Japanese version, but it was changed to [b]Scourge[/b] instead of Nemesis Prime in the English dub - despite Scourge typically being a [[scourge (transformers)|completely unrelated character]] in English releases.

title: pikmin_(creature)
body:
The titular plant-like organisms from the [[Pikmin (Series)|]] series. They come in multiple varieties and have three distinct developmental stages (leaf, bud and flower).

h5. Introduced in [[Pikmin 1]]

* [[Red Pikmin]]: The only Pikmin with noses, they are red in color and have immunity to fire.
* [[Yellow Pikmin]]: The only Pikmin with ears, they are yellow in color and are the lightest of the Pikmin. They can use small [[bomb rock]]s and have immunity to electricity. 
* [[Blue Pikmin]]: These Pikmin have mouth-like gills and are the only Pikmin who can survive being underwater. They are blue in color.

h5. Introduced in [[Pikmin 2]]

* [[White Pikmin]]: The smallest of the Pikmin, they are the fastest and have immunity to poison as well as being toxic themselves. They have large red eyes and are white in color, similar to an [[albino]].
* [[Purple Pikmin]]: The only Pikmin with hair, they are the strongest but slowest of the Pikmin with a single Purple Pikmin having the strength of ten non-purple Pikmin. They are the bulkiest of the Pikmin and are purple in color. 

h5. Introduced in [[Pikmin 3]]

* [[Rock Pikmin]]: These Pikmin are grey in color and look like rocks. They are very hard, which allows them to destroy objects and are immune to being crushed or stabbed.
* [[Winged Pikmin]]: The only Pikmin with wings, they are pink in color and have blue eyes. They can carry objects to take shortcuts and avoid enemies, but are the weakest type of Pikmin for attacking.

h5. Introduced in [[Pikmin 4]]

* [[Ice Pikmin]]: These Pikmin are made out of ice and look similar to the Rock Pikmin. They can be used to freeze enemies or water to travel across.
* [[Glow Pikmin]]: These Pikmin are bioluminescent and have a bright green ghost-like body. They are nocturnal and can be used to form energy  orbs to hit enemies.

h4. External links

* "Pikmin Wiki: Pikmin family":https://www.pikminwiki.com/Pikmin_family

title: imi_galil
body:
The [b]IMI Galil[/b] is a [[weapon family|family]] of military [[gun|firearms]] that first entered service in 1972, designed by Yisrael Galili and Yakov Lior in the late 1960s. Recognizable by its [[flip-up sight|flip-up]] aperture sights on the dust cover, vertical charging handle, rectangular one-piece handguard, skeletonized metal [[folding stock]] and a gas block with straighter profile. Based on the [[Rk62]] and similarly utilizing an AK-style gas piston system, it has been developed into several variants, such as: 

* [b]Galil AR[/b] - the original 5.56mm [[assault rifle]] with slightly-curved slimmer rectangular handguard. (post #1293721)
* [b]Galil ARM[/b] - [[light machine gun]] with notably blockier wooden handguard, carry handle and a "wire-cutter" [[bipod]]. (post #1333214)
* [b]Galil SAR "Glilon"[/b] - shorter variant of Galil AR. Smallest one is the Galil MAR. (post #1985402)
* [b]Galil 7.62[/b] - [[battle rifle]] chambered in 7.62×51mm NATO. Notice the thicker, straight box magazine. Unlike curved ones belong to the three 5.56mm counterparts. (post #6409080)
* [b][[IMI Galil Galatz|Galil Galatz]][/b] - distinctively equipped with a scope and bipod for sniper/designated marksman use. Has (post #6003226)
* This tag can also apply to the South African-produced [b]Vektor R4[/b]. (post #3181449)

h4. See also
* [[Galil (Girls' Frontline)]]
* [[Galil ACE]]
* [[Galil AR (Upotte!!)]]
* [[List of Weapons]]

title: fn_fal
body:
The [b]FAL[/b] ([i]Fusil Automatique Léger[/i], "Light Automatic Rifle") is a Belgian-designed 7.62×51mm NATO [b][[battle rifle]][/b]. It was developed between 1947-1953 by "Dieudonné Saive":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dieudonné_Saive] at [[FN Herstal]]. Known as "the right arm of the Free World", it was the second most widely used [[military]] [[rifle]] in the world (after the AK) during the [[Cold War]], being used by 77 different nations. was nearly adopted by the United States Army as well, but was rejected in favor of the M14.

Identifying characteristics include the tubular charging handle on the left side on the receiver, the shape and location of the [[muzzle device]] and front sight post, and barrel length exposed before the perforated triangular handguard (useful for differentiating it from Heckler & Koch [[weapon]]s of similar profile, such as the [[H&K G3|G3]]). This tag applies to any full-length FAL variants, such as the British L1A1, Austrian StG58, and the Israeli IMI Romat with tubular handguard.

h4. See also

* [[FAL (Girls' Frontline)]]
* [[FAL L1A1 (Upotte!!)]]

title: horikoshi_jirou
body:
[b]Horikoshi Jirou[/b] (22 June 1903 – 11 January 1982) was the main designer of several Japanese war planes, among them the Mitsubishi [[A5M]] and its successor, the legendary Mitsubishi [[A6M Zero]]; both aircraft were used by the Empire of [[Japan]] during [[World War II]]. 

Horikoshi was also involved in the design of the Zero's intended successors: the Mitsubishi [[A7M Reppuu]] carrier fighter and the land-based Mitsubishi [[J2M Raiden]] interceptor.

He graduated from (and later became professor in) the [[Tokyo University|University of Tokyo]] before joining Mitsubishi.

He is also the main subject and main protagonist of the 2013 anime film [i][[Kaze Tachinu]][/i] ([i]The Wind Rises[/i]). He is voiced by [[Anno Hideaki]] (JP) and "Joseph Gordon-Levitt":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Gordon-Levitt (EN).

title: feliz_jueves_(meme)
body:
[b]Feliz Jueves[/b] or [b]Running Asuka[/b] refers to a GIF and viral video featuring [[Neon Genesis Evangelion]] character [[Souryuu Asuka Langley]] running towards the viewer and wishing them a happy Thursday. The contrast between the innocent nature of the message and the dark themes of the series brought fame to the mashup, the original page to publish it was "Mi lugar Favorito" on Facebook and it was popularized in the [[mexico|Mexican]] and later Latin American community in the Facebook group "Testigos De Lilith" and the Facebook page "Neon Genesis Pendegelion". 

The phrase "Feliz Jueves" is occasionally posted on Thursdays across several platforms and social media.

title: sonia_greene
body:
The [[Jewish]] wife of [[H P Lovecraft]].

[b]Sonia Haft Greene Lovecraft Davis[/b] (March 16, 1883 – December 26, 1972) was an [[united_states|American]] one-time pulp fiction writer and amateur publisher, businesswoman and milliner who bankrolled several fanzines in the early twentieth century. 

She is noted for her thirteen-year marriage to American weird fiction writer H. P. Lovecraft. It began in 1923 when he was 33 and she was 40 years old. 

Sonia was also president of the United Amateur Press Association.
